{{refimprove|date=September 2016}}

The '''O'Malley Case''' was the criminal prosecution of the Chief Magistrate of Philadelphia on charges of [[malfeasance]], or serious misconduct in office by a public officer. The trials began in 1948 and continued into early 1949.

[[File:Laurence H Eldredge sworn in as Special Deputy Attorney General of Pennsylvania.jpg|thumb|Eldredge sworn in as Special Deputy Attorney General of Pennsylvania]]

The defendant was John J O'Malley, Chief Magistrate of Philadelphia; the lead prosecutor was [[Laurence Howard Eldredge]]; the first assistant prosecutor was [[Robert Lowe Kunzig]]; The second assistant prosecutor was [[Henry W. Sawyer]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/05/us/henry-sawyer-3d-dies-at-80-lawyer-in-landmark-cases.html|title=Henry Sawyer 3d Dies at 80; Lawyer in Landmark Cases|work=[[New York Times]]|date=August 5, 1999}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=July 2016}} the defense attorney was [[Lemuel Braddock Schofield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uscis.gov/history-and-genealogy/our-history-9|title=Lemuel B. Schofield|work=[[United States Citizenship and Immigration Services]]}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=July 2016}}

[[File:Laurence Eldredge, Bob Kunzig, and Henry Sawyer confer in court, O'Malley behind.jpg|thumb|Eldredge, Kunzig, and Sawyer confer in court, O'Malley behind]]

[[File:State Opens O'Malley Case.jpg|thumb|''Daily News'' headline story on the case]]

